      "value": "Valley Center-Pauma Unified is a mid-sized, rural K-12 district in the North Inland region of San Diego County. About 655 of its students have an IEP, and 127 of them \u2014 roughly 19% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 23% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-17T18:35:20Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard"
      ],
      "value": "About 23% of autistic students in this district are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, with around 4% in a fully separate setting, so many spend a substantial part of the day in specialized settings. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 46% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 131 points below standard in English and 168 below in math, while students overall were 63 and 105 points below. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 34% (compared with 29% for all students) and suspended at about 6% (compared with 3%)."
    }
  },
